---
import { getPageContract } from '../config/site'
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'

const page = getPageContract('about')
---

<BaseLayout description={page.description} pageTitle={page.title} path={page.path}>
  <article class="about">
    <h1>About</h1>

    <p>
      I'm Stephen Sawyer. I build self-hostable software for people who want the
      system to run on their hardware, keep inspectable data, and stay understandable
      after the launch adrenaline wears off.
    </p>

    <p>
      Most new work lives in three lanes. <strong>Python</strong> handles automation,
      integrations, APIs, and backend logic where speed of iteration matters.
      <strong>Go</strong> handles networking, daemons, observability, and long-running
      operator runtimes. Browser-facing surfaces use <strong>TypeScript</strong>,
      <strong>Bun</strong>, and <strong>Astro</strong>, with <strong>Vue</strong>
      reserved for interactions that truly earn client-side state.
    </p>

    <h2>What I care about</h2>

    <p>
      <strong>Ownership.</strong> If you can't run it yourself, you don't own it.
      Every product I build is designed to run on a single machine under your control.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Boring infrastructure.</strong> Novel architecture is a liability until
      proven otherwise. I want the deployment that survives Tuesday night, not the
      diagram that looks clever on a whiteboard.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>The data layer is the truth layer.</strong> Relational data, explicit
      schema, query paths you can inspect. If you can't trace a value through the
      system, it's too clever.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Shipping beats planning.</strong> A working system you iterate on
      outranks a perfect design doc. Complexity must be earned -- every abstraction
      needs justification beyond "might be useful someday."
    </p>

    <h2>The stack</h2>

    <p>
      The default browser lane is <strong>TypeScript + Bun + Astro</strong>, with
      Vue added only for substantial interactive UI. The default terminal lane is
      <strong>OpenTUI + TypeScript + Bun</strong> when the operator workflow belongs
      in a real terminal surface instead of a plain CLI.
    </p>

    <p>
      For data, I reach for <strong>PostgreSQL</strong> by default on products that
      are meant to grow, and <strong>SQLite</strong> when a tool is intentionally
      local-first, embedded, or single-user. Either way, the schema is explicit and
      the query paths stay inspectable.
    </p>

    <p>
      On the browser side, Astro owns pages, delivery, and first render. Vue only
      shows up when the browser UI needs real client-side state. No SPA shell by
      reflex, no analytics junk, no gratuitous hydration.
    </p>

    <p>
      This site now runs live on an Ubuntu VM using Astro static output, a Docker
      container, host-level Caddy, and Cloudflare in front. That is the kind of
      deployment shape I like: explicit, inspectable, and boring enough to trust.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
